Executive Summary

This paper examines a recurring public claim in contemporary AI discourse: that large language models (“LLMs”) can help a user “learn almost anything.” On its face, this statement appears uplifting, democratic, and mildly evangelical. Upon inspection, however, it contains a substantial and highly flammable ambiguity.

The ambiguity concerns the word learn.

A user may indeed consult a language model to gain familiarity with vocabulary, broad concepts, procedural overviews, historical context, and beginner-level explanation. These are legitimate instructional functions. But the public rhetoric surrounding such systems increasingly elides the distinction between:
	•	conceptual introduction,
	•	exam-style tutoring,
	•	procedural narration,
	•	regulated professional training,
	•	hands-on supervised apprenticeship,
	•	and genuine operational competence under real-world constraints.

This elision is not trivial. It is the difference between “I now understand what a valve is” and “I am about to alter a live gas installation to code.”

Accordingly, this paper introduces the doctrine of Pedagogical Overreach: the tendency of LLM evangelism to imply educational scope beyond what the system can actually deliver, especially in domains where expertise depends not merely on words, but on tacit judgment, embodied practice, regulatory compliance, situational awareness, and the cost structure of error.

The central finding is as follows:

A system that can explain a discipline is not thereby capable of training a person to perform that discipline safely, lawfully, or competently.

This document further finds that the slogan “it can help you learn almost anything” becomes materially misleading when applied without distinction to high-risk, regulated, or materially embodied activities such as:
	•	neurosurgery,
	•	gas fitting and leak response,
	•	electrical work to code,
	•	aviation maintenance,
	•	high-voltage systems isolation,
	•	anesthesia administration,
	•	confined-space entry procedures,
	•	industrial rigging,
	•	structural engineering sign-off,
	•	hazardous materials response,
	•	forensic chain-of-custody handling,
	•	neonatal intensive care,
	•	and catching whatever one has, in a moment of gastrointestinal administrative collapse, inadvertently ejected.

The issue, in short, is not whether LLMs can be educational. The issue is whether the public has been invited to confuse explanatory fluency with transferable competence.

This confusion is designated throughout as the Semantic Trillionaire Problem: the condition in which infinite words create the impression of infinite capability.

