1. Statement of the Problem

Recent public discourse has advanced a proposition of heroic breadth: that LLMs can help a person learn nearly any subject. Such claims often present themselves as obvious, modern, and too generous to oppose. But once applied to any domain with accreditation standards, practical risk, or law attached, the proposition begins to emit smoke.

The problem is not that the statement is entirely false. The problem is that it is true in a weak sense and then rhetorically spent in a strong sense.

This paper therefore distinguishes between two claims:

1.1 Weak Claim

A language model can often provide useful explanations, summaries, examples, and study support across a wide range of topics.

1.2 Strong Claim

A language model can serve as a meaningful teaching pathway toward competent performance in almost any real-world domain, including those requiring licensed judgment, practical execution, or exact regulatory adherence.

The first claim is often defensible.
The second claim is where the lawsuits begin to clear their throats.

⸻

2. The Core Distinction: Explanation Versus Formation

A machine that can speak about a thing is not necessarily capable of forming a person into someone who can do that thing.

This distinction has been scandalously neglected.

2.1 Explanation

Explanation involves language: definitions, principles, examples, analogies, rough sequences, common pitfalls, and conceptual simplification.

2.2 Formation

Formation involves transformation of the learner into a competent practitioner. This may require:
	•	supervised repetition,
	•	sensory discrimination,
	•	procedural timing,
	•	manual dexterity,
	•	tacit judgment,
	•	domain-specific caution,
	•	calibration against reality,
	•	correction by qualified humans,
	•	exposure to edge cases,
	•	and the moral burden of consequences.

An LLM can produce the first category abundantly. It cannot independently supply the second in many critical domains, because the second is not merely linguistic. It is institutional, embodied, environmental, and often legal.

This gap is the site of Pedagogical Overreach.

⸻

3. The “Almost Anything” Inflation Mechanism

The phrase “almost anything” functions as a universal solvent. It dissolves category boundaries until studying organic chemistry, replacing a consumer light switch, and clipping an aneurysm appear to differ only in prompt engineering.

This mechanism follows a predictable sequence:
	1.	The model explains a concept well.
	2.	The user experiences understandable amazement.
	3.	Amazement broadens into confidence.
	4.	Confidence broadens into generalized educational trust.
	5.	Educational trust broadens into procedural reliance.
	6.	Procedural reliance encounters reality.
	7.	Reality, unlike the model, does not autocomplete.

This is not a bug in a single user. It is a rhetorical hazard built into the mode of praise.

