4. Domains the Model Can Discuss but Cannot Truly Teach to Competent Practice

The Committee has determined that the following classes of activity are especially vulnerable to misuse under the banner of “learning almost anything.”

4.1 Brain Surgery

The model may explain:
	•	neuroanatomical terminology,
	•	common indications for procedures,
	•	broad descriptions of surgical approaches,
	•	post-operative concepts,
	•	landmark structures,
	•	and the difference between alarming and very alarming.

The model cannot thereby teach:
	•	live tissue handling,
	•	intraoperative judgment,
	•	complication management,
	•	instrument feel,
	•	emergency adaptation,
	•	irreversible-risk prioritization,
	•	or the moral significance of millimeters.

A person who has “learned brain surgery” from text generation is, in practical terms, a person whose confidence has advanced faster than their licensing.

4.2 Plumbing

The model may teach:
	•	what traps do,
	•	how venting works,
	•	the names of fittings,
	•	why gradients matter,
	•	and how not everything wet is a feature.

The model cannot reliably teach:
	•	the feel of a properly seated connection,
	•	local code interpretation,
	•	site-specific constraints,
	•	how old systems lie,
	•	how previous owners have sinned,
	•	or why water always finds the one place you assumed it would not.

4.3 Gas Safety to Exact Regulatory Standards

The phrase “to exact regulatory standards” is where the whole fantasy collapses like wet cardboard.

A model may provide high-level educational information about gas systems, safety principles, and regulatory frameworks. It cannot substitute for licensed training, current code knowledge, jurisdiction-specific requirements, testing protocols, or supervised practice. It especially cannot guarantee that its explanation is complete, current, lawful, or safe in the exact place where a person is standing with a wrench and misplaced optimism.

Here the distinction is absolute:

orientation is not authorization.

4.4 Electrical Work

The model can explain:
	•	voltage, current, resistance,
	•	breaker logic,
	•	grounding concepts,
	•	and why touching some things once is enough.

It cannot grant:
	•	lockout-tagout discipline,
	•	live-work judgment,
	•	code-compliant installation skill,
	•	field diagnosis in legacy systems,
	•	or legal sign-off authority.

4.5 Aviation Maintenance

An LLM may produce a persuasive paragraph on turbine systems. It cannot smell hydraulic fluid, detect tool-control failures, verify torques in context, or assume legal responsibility for an aircraft leaving the ground.

4.6 Industrial Rigging

The model can discuss load paths. It cannot hear a bad lift. It cannot feel a shifting center of gravity. It cannot stand beneath the thing it encouraged.

4.7 Midwifery, Anesthesia, Intensive Care, and Other Activities in Which “Close Enough” Is a Coroner’s Accent

These domains involve live, dynamic human systems under pressure, ambiguity, and compounding consequences. Textual guidance does not equal accountable care.

4.8 Catching Whatever One Has Suddenly Expelled

The Committee is aware that this final example is structurally comic. It is also analytically useful. It demonstrates that the boast “you can learn almost anything” eventually includes absurd tasks whose practical success depends on timing, embodiment, and circumstance rather than discursive explanation.

A model may offer hand-eye coordination tips. It remains unclear whether this constitutes a curriculum.

