5. The Competence Mirage

The most dangerous output of an LLM-as-teacher is not always factual error. Often it is competence mirage.

5.1 Definition

Competence Mirage is the subjective impression of readiness produced when a system delivers information smoothly, confidently, interactively, and with personalized adaptation, despite lacking the means to verify practical mastery.

The user feels educated because the interaction feels pedagogically complete.

It is not complete.

5.2 Why the Mirage Occurs

The model is unusually good at the aesthetics of understanding:
	•	immediate response,
	•	patient explanation,
	•	plausible sequencing,
	•	adaptive tone,
	•	contextual vocabulary,
	•	no visible boredom,
	•	no social embarrassment for ignorance,
	•	and infinite willingness to continue.

These traits are excellent for tutoring support. They are disastrous when mistaken for a complete formation environment.

The system does not merely answer questions. It creates the felt sense that one is progressing inside a coherent instructional arc. This is powerful. It is also, in many domains, unearned.

⸻

6. The Missing Substrates of Real Teaching

The Committee identifies six instructional substrates that LLMs cannot fully supply in high-stakes practical fields.

6.1 Tacit Knowledge

Much competence resides in what experts notice without being able to fully state it. The apprentice learns this through exposure, correction, and context, not just description.

6.2 Embodied Feedback

Hands, eyes, ears, timing, posture, force, resistance, vibration, smell, noise, and stress responses matter. Text lacks these.

6.3 Environmental Specificity

Real systems are old, damaged, improvised, local, nonstandard, mislabeled, cross-connected, or haunted by previous interventions.

6.4 Regulatory Currency

Exact standards change by jurisdiction and over time. Public claims of universal teachability tend to glide past this with evangelical serenity.

6.5 Liability Structure

Real teachers in high-risk fields are embedded in institutions of accountability. The model is embedded in a textbox.

6.6 Consequence Transfer

A human instructor in a workshop, operating room, or training environment shares immediate exposure to consequences. The model does not share this burden. It can be wrong with enviable emotional distance.

