8. Public Rhetoric and the Inflation of Scope

A recurring genre of commentary praises LLMs in terms so expansive that ordinary category distinctions disappear. One begins with “great study aid” and ends with an implied universal apprenticeship machine.

The following translation table is entered into the record.

Public Claim	Operational Meaning	Risk
“It can help you learn almost anything.”	It can explain many topics in fluent language.	Users may infer competence transfer where none exists.
“It’s like having a tutor for everything.”	It is interactive and responsive.	A tutor is mistaken for a training regime.
“Anyone can level up fast now.”	Access to explanations is easier.	Access is confused with qualification.
“This changes expertise.”	The front end of learning is compressed.	Institutions of competence are rhetorically bypassed.
“You can just ask it.”	It is always available.	Availability is mistaken for authority.

The issue is not malicious deception in every instance. The issue is systematic ambiguity combined with social overexcitement, which historically has an excellent track record of producing avoidable nonsense.

