9. The Regulatory Problem

The phrase “to exact regulatory standards” deserves independent condemnation.

An LLM cannot responsibly promise exact compliance across shifting legal jurisdictions, codes, editions, interpretations, enforcement habits, site conditions, and field realities. Yet the public often speaks as if a sufficiently earnest prompt and a cup of tea can bridge this gap.

This paper therefore states the following principle:

Any claim that an LLM can teach regulated, high-risk practice “to exact standards” without supervised human credentialing is institutionally unserious.

It may still be viral. It may still sound empowering. It remains unserious.

