10. Methodology

The Office conducted a twelve-month mixed-methods assessment using the Synthetic Apprenticeship Inflation Index (SAII), the Competence Mirage Severity Scale (CMSS), and the Bureaucratic Alarm Threshold for Unlicensed Confidence (BATUC).

10.1 Experimental Protocol

Participants were exposed to model-based instruction in increasingly hazardous domains:
	1.	low-stakes conceptual knowledge,
	2.	practical household maintenance,
	3.	regulated technical trades,
	4.	invasive clinical procedures,
	5.	emergency response settings,
	6.	advanced improvisational fecal interception.

After each phase, participants reported:
	•	confidence,
	•	perceived readiness,
	•	actual performance,
	•	and degree of surprise when reality failed to behave like a chatbot.

10.2 Principal Findings

The model reliably increased user confidence.
It less reliably increased user competence.
The gap widened as consequences became more material, embodied, regulated, or irreversible.

This gap is now formally indexed as the Fluency-Competence Divergence (FCD).

