11. Findings

The Committee adopts the following findings:

Finding 1

LLMs can often support introductory learning and conceptual clarification across many subjects.

Finding 2

This support is routinely overstated in public discourse through vague uses of the word “learn.”

Finding 3

In high-risk, embodied, or regulated domains, explanatory fluency does not amount to competence formation.

Finding 4

The user may experience a false sense of readiness because the model is highly effective at producing the feeling of educational momentum.

Finding 5

Claims that such systems can teach exact compliance, practical mastery, or professional readiness without supervised human structures are materially inflationary.

Finding 6

The more expensive the mistake, the less acceptable it is to confuse tutoring with training.

Finding 7

A tool that can describe a discipline may still be incapable of teaching it in the only sense that matters when something can explode, bleed, collapse, leak, or litigate.

