14. Conclusion

The strongest version of the argument is simple.

LLMs can often help people understand things.
They cannot, by virtue of being able to explain things, reliably train people to perform all those things in the world.

That distinction must be guarded with institutional hostility.

The public phrase “you can learn almost anything” collapses too many categories into one glowing promise. It bundles conceptual orientation together with operational readiness, and beginner comprehension together with professional competence. In domains where error is trivial, this is mostly annoying. In domains where error leaks gas, severs arteries, voids insurance, drops loads, or mismanages living tissue, it becomes indefensible.

The issue is not whether the tool is useful. It plainly is.
The issue is whether usefulness has been rhetorically inflated into universal teachability.

It has.

Accordingly, the Committee issues the following final principle for publication, citation, and placement above all innovation panels:

A language model may teach about a practice without being capable of teaching a person to do that practice safely, lawfully, or well.

And, for avoidance of doubt:

A machine that can explain brain surgery is not a brain surgery teacher. It is a talking pamphlet with delusions of faculty.

